  <div class="article-header">
    <div class="tags">
      <span class="tag" style="background:#FAC775;color:#412402;">Reaction of the week</span>
      <span class="tag" style="background:#E1F5EE;color:#085041;">Oscillating Reaction</span>
    </div>
    <h1 class="article-title">The Briggs-Rauscher Reaction: Chemistry's Color-Changing Clock</h1>
    <p class="article-desc">Witness one of chemistry's most spectacular demonstrations as this oscillating reaction rhythmically cycles through amber, blue, and clear colors like a chemical heartbeat.</p>
    <div class="meta">8 min read · Includes video · 3 research links</div>
  </div>

  <div class="section-label">The reaction</div>
  <div class="equation-box">
    <span class="eq-part" style="color:#AFA9EC;">IO₃⁻ + 2H₂O₂ + CH₂(COOH)₂ + H⁺</span>
    <span class="eq-arrow">→</span>
    <span class="eq-part" style="color:#9FE1CB;">ICH(COOH)₂ + 2O₂ + 3H₂O</span>
  </div>

  <p class="body-text">Imagine a chemical reaction that behaves like a metronome, rhythmically changing colors every few seconds for minutes on end. The Briggs-Rauscher reaction is exactly that – a mesmerizing oscillating reaction discovered in 1972 that cycles through three distinct colors: clear (colorless), amber (yellow), and deep blue, creating what chemists call a "chemical clock."</p>
  
  <p class="body-text">This reaction involves potassium iodate, hydrogen peroxide, malonic acid, manganese sulfate, and sulfuric acid. When mixed together, these seemingly ordinary chemicals create an extraordinary display that demonstrates one of chemistry's most fascinating phenomena: how chemical systems can exhibit periodic behavior, much like the biological rhythms we see in living organisms.</p>

  <div class="callout">
    <div class="callout-title">Oscillating Reactions</div>
    <div class="callout-text">Unlike typical reactions that proceed steadily from reactants to products, oscillating reactions cycle through different states repeatedly. The concentrations of intermediate species rise and fall in a periodic pattern, creating the color changes we observe. This happens because of complex feedback mechanisms where the products of one step influence earlier steps in the reaction sequence.</div>
  </div>

  <p class="body-text">The color changes occur due to the formation and consumption of different iodine-containing species. During the clear phase, iodate ions (IO₃⁻) are slowly reduced. In the amber phase, iodine (I₂) forms and creates the yellow-brown color. The dramatic blue phase occurs when iodine reacts with starch (often added as an indicator) to form the characteristic blue iodine-starch complex. The cycle then repeats as the system oscillates between these states, typically continuing for 5-10 minutes before finally settling into a steady blue color.</p>

